The NullReferenceException is thrown at line 225 of StudentsController.cs, which is inside the `try` block but the exception propagates because `student.FirstMidName` access on a null object. Let me look at the code:

```csharp
public ActionResult DeleteConfirmed(int id)
{
    try
    {
        Student student = db.Students.Find(id);
        var studentName = $"{student.FirstMidName} {student.LastName}"; // <-- line 213, NRE here
        db.Students.Remove(student);
        db.SaveChanges();
        return RedirectToAction("Index");
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        return RedirectToAction("Index");
    }
}
```

The stack trace points to line 225, but the actual problem is that `student` is null when we try to access `FirstMidName`. The try-catch is there, but it's catching and silently redirecting, which masks the real issue—the `Find()` call returned null because the student ID doesn't exist in the database. Looking at the actual code structure, the NullReferenceException is happening on line 213 where I'm trying to access `student.FirstMidName` and `student.LastName` — but `student` is null because `db.Students.Find(id)` didn't find a matching record. The catch block does handle the exception, but the error trace is pointing to line 225 in the Trace.TraceError call itself. Looking at the actual file content with line numbers to verify the stack trace. The DeleteConfirmed method wraps the student deletion in a try-catch block that logs errors to the trace and sets a TempData error message before redirecting back to the Index action. So the second NRE happens when trying to set `TempData["ErrorMessage"]` because `TempData` itself is null—the test infrastructure doesn't have the TempData provider set up. I need to mock or initialize `TempData` in the test setup to prevent this, or accept that the test will fail at that point. The simplest fix is to assign a mock `ITempDataDictionary` to the controller's `TempData` property.

